<div class="contain" style="text-indent:1cm; text-align:justify;">
	<p></p>
	<b>Editorial policy</b>
	<p>
		&nbsp;The SEAJ Science journal is published twice a year in June and December by the Faculty of Science, Udon Thani Rajabhat University, Thailand. Work involving human or animal subjects requires that the appropriate ethical committee permissions are included in the manuscript. Articles which have already been published, or which are under consideration, by other journals should not be submitted. Articles published in the SEAJ Science journal should not subsequently be submitted to other journals.
	</p>
	<b>Types of manuscript</b>
	<p>
		Manuscripts may be submitted in different forms as follows:<br/>
		<li><b>Review Articles </b>  should be 12 point double-spaced A4 text, including all tables, figures and references. Self-referencing should be limit to 10%.</li>
		<li><b>Research Papers</b>  should not exceed 20 pages of 12 point double-spaced A4 text, including all tables, figures and references.</li>
		<li><b>Short Communications </b> should not exceed 8 pages of 12 point double-spaced A4 text, including not more than 2 tables and 2 figures. </li>
	</p>
	<b>Presentation</b>
	<p>
		Research papers should not exceed 5000 words including references (excluding the abstract and table and figure legends). Review articles should not exceed 8000 words and short communications should not exceed 2000 words.  The font must be 12 point Times New Roman for text, typed in double spacing format with all pages numbered consecutively, including those containing acknowledgements, references, tables and figures. All lines on all pages must be numbered in a single sequence. Manuscripts with mathematical content should use an accepted equation editor or be submitted using LaTeX. Manuscripts must to be submitted in .docx format (Word 2007 or higher). 
	</p>
	<p>
		Manuscripts for review must consist of a single file with figure and table legends included at the end of this file on separate pages.  The figure and table files must be uploaded separately. Please note that separate high resolution figure files will be required to gain acceptance (see below). Typescripts must be in English. The Editors reserve the right to modify accepted manuscripts that do not conform to the scientific, technical, stylistic or grammatical standards as described here and these minor alterations may not be seen by the authors until the proof stage.
	</p>
	<b>Typescript</b>
	<p>
		The typescript should follow the conventional form and must include: 
		<br>
		<ul style="text-indent:0;">
			<li><b>A title page</b> should include the name(s) of the author(s), a concise and informative title, the affiliation(s) and address(es) of all author(s) as well as the e-mail address, telephone and fax numbers of the corresponding author.</li>
			<li><b>An Abstract </b> should contain between 150 and 250 words and should not include any undefined abbreviations or unspecified references.</li>
			<li>A maximum of six <b>Keywords</b> should be suggested.</li>
			<li><b>An Introduction </b>should not provide a review of the field, it should introduce the reader to the aims of the study and elaborate the context of the work to be described.</li>
			<li><b>A Materials and Methods </b> section should be sufficient to allow the work to be replicated, but should not repeat information which is described fully elsewhere.</li>
			<li>The description of <b>Results</b> should be restricted to a factual account of the findings obtained and the text must not duplicate information given in Tables and Figures.</li>
			<li><b>A Discussion </b> section should point out the significance of the results in relation to the motivations for undertaking the research.</li>
			<li><b>Any Acknowledgments </b> of people, financial grants etc. should be placed in a separate section on the title page. The names of all funding organizations should be written in full.</li>
			<li><b>The References </b> should be alphabetized by the last names of the first author of each work and examples are given below	</li>
			<ul>
				<li><b>Journal article</b>	Poonlaphdecha S, Ribas A. (2016) Yeasts in amphibians are common: isolation and the first molecular characterization from Thailand. Acta Herpetologica, 11(1): 81-84.
				</li>
				<li><b>Article by DOI</b>	Ribas A, Saijuntha W, Agatsuma T, Prantlová V, Poonlaphdecha S. (2016) Rodents as a source of <i>Salmonella</i> contamination in wet markets in Thailand. Vector-Borne and Zoonotic Diseases, doi:10.1089/vbz.2015.1894.
				</li>
				<li><b>Book</b>	Nowak R. (1999) Walker’s mammals of the world, 6th edn. Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, Maryland.
				</li>
				<li><b>Book chapter</b>	Bellocq J, Ribas A, Baird, S.J.E. (2012) New insights intro parasitism in the house mouse hybrid zone. In: Morand S, Krasnov BR, eds. Evolution of the House Mouse Series: Cambridge Studies in Morphology and Molecules: New Paradigms in Evolutionary Bio (No. 3). Cambridge University Press. Cambridge. Pp. 455-81.
				</li>
				<li><b>Online document</b>	Rambaut A. (1996) Se-Al. Sequence alignment editor. Ver 2.0a11. University of Oxford, Oxford, UK. Available from: http://tree.bio.ed.ac.uk/software/seal/
				</li>
			</ul>
			<li><b>References in articles </b> should use the following scheme:</li>
			<ul>
				<li><b>For 1 or 2 author(s)</b>	Poonlaphdecha & Ribas (2016) or (Nowak, 1999)
				</li>
				<li><b>For more than 2 authors</b>	Ribas et al. (2016) or (Morand et al., 2010)
				</li>
			</ul>
		</ul>
		<b>Headings</b>
		<p>	Please use no more than three levels of headings.</p>
		<b>Abbreviations</b>
		<p>	It should be defined at their first mention and used consistently thereafter.</p>
		<b>Tables</b>
		<p>These must fit the page size (A4) without undue reduction. Oversize tables will not be accepted. Tables should be kept simple and where possible the use of vertical lines should be avoided. Tables should be referred to as Table 1, Table 2, etc., and any subsections as (a), (b), etc. Footnotes in tables should be indicated by superscripts a, b, etc.</p>
		<b>Figures</b>
		<p>Figures should be submitted as separate electronic files and figure legends should be included at the end of the main manuscript file. Illustrations may be line drawings or photographs and should be numbered consecutively in the text as Fig. 1, Fig. 2 etc. Component parts of figures should be labelled (a), (b) etc. Captions for figures, which should be self-explanatory, must be typed, double spaced, on a separate page. Half-tones and combination artwork should be supplied in TIFF format at a minimum resolution of 300 dpi and 600 dpi, respectively.</p>
		<b><i>Note: Manuscripts that do not conform to these guidelines will be rejected at the submission stage.</i></b><br>
		<p></p>

		<b>Decisions and invitations to revise</b>
		<p>All submissions are subject to peer review and authors can expect a decision, or an explanation for the delay, within 3 months of receipt. If revision is necessary, the corresponding author should submit the revised manuscript within 2 months unless there are special reasons for a delay, which should be agreed to in advance by the Editor. Papers not received within 2 months may be treated as new submissions and sent for further evaluation by new referees.</p>
		<b>Pre-submission English-language editing</b>
		<p>	It is strongly recommended that papers be proof-read by a native English speaker, or at least someone proficient in the English language, before being submitted so as to avoid the possibility of rejection on language rather than scientific grounds. </p>
	</p>
